Multiple references confirm that the digastric muscle depresses the mandible, especially when acting synergistically with other suprahyoid muscles or under conditions where the hyoid is stabilized. While it also elevates the hyoid, its effect on mandibular depression is consistently emphasized across several anatomical descriptions involving mastication, swallowing, and jaw opening. No evidence supports protrusion or side-to-side movement of the mandible as a primary action of the digastric muscle.

